Activity B checklist: Design documents

18. Create visual/interface designs

The brief says your design documents must include visual/interface designs.  ￼

Create wireframes or mock-ups for the main screens, such as:
	•	homepage
	•	product listing page
	•	product details page
	•	basket/checkout
	•	collection or delivery selection
	•	login/register
	•	customer account
	•	producer dashboard
	•	stock edit page
	•	orders page

Make sure the layout is clear enough for a third-party developer to build.

19. Create data requirements

The brief says you must include data requirements.  ￼

You should show:
	•	the data the system needs
	•	what tables/entities you need
	•	important fields
	•	keys and relationships

Likely entities:
	•	Customer
	•	Producer
	•	Product
	•	Category
	•	Order
	•	OrderItem
	•	DeliverySlot or CollectionSlot
	•	LoyaltyReward
	•	StockUpdate

20. Create algorithm designs

The brief says you need a selection of algorithm designs and you should limit them to a maximum of five complex problems.  ￼

Choose the most important logic parts, for example:
	•	placing an order
	•	checking stock before confirming an order
	•	calculating loyalty discounts
	•	assigning delivery or collection slots
	•	producer updating stock and product details

You can use flowcharts, pseudocode, or both.

21. Create a test strategy

The brief says you must include a test strategy, and it must show the order you plan to test the system and the types of tests for each component. It does not need every single test case, just a sensible selection.  ￼

So include:
	•	testing order
	•	component to be tested
	•	type of test
	•	purpose of test
	•	expected outcome

A simple testing order could be:
	1.	database and data validation
	2.	login/register
	3.	product browsing
	4.	basket and checkout
	5.	delivery/collection booking
	6.	loyalty scheme
	7.	producer dashboard
	8.	full end-to-end testing

22. Make sure the solution is detailed enough

Before finishing, check that your documents:
	•	make sense to non-technical people
	•	contain enough detail for technical people
	•	are detailed enough for a third-party developer
	•	clearly show front-end and back-end features
	•	are realistic for the brief

This is directly required by the exam paper.  ￼

